(57, 'The Hundred Years War IV: Cursed Kings by Jonathan Sumption, review: ''astonishing''', 'How do you greet the man who, in the space of just five years, has humiliated you in battle, conquered half your kingdom and now stands before you, waiting to be formally endorsed as regent to rule in your stead and then become king after you, disinheriti', 'TELEGRAPH.CO.UK', '2015-09-16 19:00:00', 4, 13, 0, 'cursed_small.jpg', 'cursed.jpg', '', '', 'One of the great delights of this magnificent fourth volume of Jonathan Sumption’s The Hundred Years War is the author’s ability to pick just the right quotation to illustrate his narrative.', 'How do you greet the man who, in the space of just five years, has humiliated you in battle, conquered half your kingdom and now stands before you, waiting to be formally endorsed as regent to rule in your stead and then become king after you, disinheriting your own son in the process? In the great assembly at Troyes, flanked by his daughter who had been granted as a bride to the conqueror, and the councillors gathered nervously around the throne on which he had for so long been “posed like a doll”, Charles VI of France struggled to find something to say. “Oh, it’s you,” he said eventually to Henry V. “Well, since you are here, welcome!”\r\n\r\nOne of the great delights of this magnificent fourth volume of Jonathan Sumption’s The Hundred Years War is the author’s ability to pick just the right quotation to illustrate his narrative. The sheer banality of Charles’s remark, neatly juxtaposed with the solemnity of what was undoubtedly the most important diplomatic occasion of his reign, brings home the quandary facing the French throughout the period covered by this book (1399-1422). At a time when all secular power and authority was vested in the monarch, what do you do when he is unfit to rule? \r\n\r\nFor 30 years, ever since his first episode in 1392, Charles had suffered from intermittent and increasingly lengthy periods of mental illness that left him, in Sumption’s own arresting phrase, “a mannequin of authority, at once indispensable and useless”. Charles’s mental “absences” created a void at the heart of government, which his greedy relatives fought each other to fill. \r\n\r\nThe king’s brother, Louis of Orléans, built up vast estates and acquired royal revenues which formed nine-tenths of his income; his greatest rival, their uncle Philip of Burgundy, used his ascendancy to siphon off more than a tenth of the crown’s annual revenues into his own private purse. Neither of them could afford to allow the other to acquire exclusive control of the king’s person, but what began as a political battle for access to the crown’s largesse became a bitter blood feud between the houses of Orléans and Burgundy after the murder of Louis of Orléans by Philip’s son John in 1407. Their personal quarrel dragged the kingdom into the abyss of a civil war that, even by the standards of the day, was extraordinarily brutal, with the defeated executed as traitors by their fellow countrymen.', 'null', '0', '0', '1', '0', '1'),
(58, 'Marisa Acocella Marchetto on Skewering New York Media and Our Cell Phone–Obsessed Culture', 'Marisa Acocella Marchetto, the New Yorker cartoonist and creator of the new graphic novel Ann Tenna, started drawing as a young girl in New Jersey.', 'VOGUE.COM', '2015-09-16 16:00:00', 4, 13, 0, 'anntenna_small.jpg', 'anntenna.jpg', '', '', 'Marisa Acocella Marchetto, the New Yorker cartoonist and creator of the new graphic novel Ann Tenna, started drawing as a young girl in New Jersey. Her mother was a shoe designer for Delman, and Marchetto would sketch “fabulous women” like the ones she saw in the trend reports her mom compiled.', 'Marisa Acocella Marchetto, the New Yorker cartoonist and creator of the new graphic novel Ann Tenna, started drawing as a young girl in New Jersey. Her mother was a shoe designer for Delman, and Marchetto would sketch “fabulous women” like the ones she saw in the trend reports her mom compiled. “The first drawing I ever did was of a shoe,” Marchetto tells Vogue.com by phone. It wasn’t until her family took a vacation to Bermuda, and ended up inside a house that belonged to the legendary cartoonist James Thurber, with some of his work hanging on the walls, that she realized that she could add words to her images. “That was an epiphany.”\r\n\r\nBut then Marchetto grew up, and was hired at the advertising firm J. Walter Thompson. (Her boss was then creative director James Patterson: “Everybody would be like, ‘Oh, Jim, he gets up early in the morning to write these books. . . . Do you think they’ll ever go anywhere?’ ”) The commercials she worked on featured the type of women she once sketched; to the chagrin of her superiors, she found the ladies in the ads far more fascinating than the products she was being paid to promote. She was miserable.\r\n\r\nThen, another epiphany: On New Year’s Eve of her 30th year, “I lit a votive candle and channeled all the higher spirits. I would write in my journal all the things I wanted for the [coming] year.” She found herself doodling a picture of a woman with a gun in her mouth, captioned with the line: “‘She was a little upset during the meeting.” Click. “I was like, Oh, my God! I should have been a cartoonist all along!’” Carried away, Marchetto leaned over her journal and lit her dangling tresses on fire. “I had long frayed hair,” she remembers, laughing. “Sort of angled, but all one length. I had to get a shag.”\r\n\r\nIt’s a story that carries extra resonance in the context of Marchetto’s new book, Ann Tenna, the follow-up to Cancer Vixen, her 2006 memoir about receiving a breast cancer diagnosis just ahead of her wedding to her now-husband, Da Silvano restauranteur Silvano Marchetto. The new novel is about a striving, attention-addicted, body image—obsessed woman named Ann Tenna, founder of a sinister Gawker-like gossip site called Eyemauler. At the top of the dirt-digging media heap, Ann thinks she’s got it made—a glamorous career, sycophantic friends, an engagement to a sleazy, in-high-demand party photographer named Zim—until she gets into a horrible car accident, suffers a traumatic brain injury, and goes into a coma. While unconscious, she visits a higher realm, meets her other half, the cosmic Super Ann, and gets her orders from above: Go back to earth and become transmissionary, a beacon of love and light in a world overrun by mean-spirited gossip and the technological devices that help keep us addicted to it. She also learns that her unruly red hair actually serves a very important purpose: It’s an antenna that will help her communicate with the spectral Super Ann, and communicate her messages of enlightenment to the rest of the world.\r\n\r\nBack on earth, Ann wakes up to find her head partially shaved from brain surgery (she fixes that situation not with a shag, but with a groovy, assymetrical, Ziggy Stardust–inspired mullet) and the voice of Super Ann constantly in her ear, reminding her of her mission. Can she separate out her own sense of self-worth from constant media adulation? Can she see Zim for the dirtbag he really is? Can she disconnect from the empty life she once loved in order to fully reconnect with her higher self? No spoilers here: Read the book. It’s a visually explosive, pun-loving, fashion-filled frolic through heaven, hell, and the strangest place of all: 21st-century New York City.', 'null', '0', '0', '1', '0', '1'),
(59, 'Rosalind Franklin would be ''astonished''', 'Family of scientist whose key role in discovering DNA', 'TELEGRAPH.CO.UK', '2015-09-16 16:00:00', 4, 14, 0, 'kidman_small.jpg', 'kidman.jpg', '', '', 'The family of Rosalind Franklin, the British scientist whose pioneering work is being celebrated in a new Nicole Kidman play, say she would be "astonished" to be cast as a feminist icon because she never considered herself a victim of sexism.', 'The family of Rosalind Franklin, the British scientist whose pioneering work is being celebrated in a new Nicole Kidman play, say she would be "astonished" to be cast as a feminist icon because she never considered herself a victim of sexism.\r\nKidman stars as Franklin in Photograph 51, the West End production that begins its official run on Monday night.\r\nThe British scientist played a key role in discovering the structure of DNA while working at King''s College London, but was effectively written out of history. She died of cancer in 1958 and three male colleagues, Francis Crick, James Watson and Maurice Wilkins, went on to claim the credit and the Nobel Prize.\r\nKidman has said she wants to shine a light on the role of Franklin and women like her whose quiet hard work has been overshadowed by pushier men.', 'null', '0', '0', '1', '0', '1'),
(60, 'It''s not just you, Roger Moore', 'There is a natural tendency for ageing performers to think that the people who come after them are a bit rubbish; and at 87, Sir Roger may be approaching the age at which one’s bat-squeak clarity of hearing begins to dim.', 'TELEGRAPH.CO.UK', '2015-09-16 16:00:00', 4, 14, 0, 'roger_small.jpg', 'roger.jpg', '', '', 'There is a natural tendency for ageing performers to think that the people who come after them are a bit rubbish; and at 87, Sir Roger may be approaching the age at which one’s bat-squeak clarity of hearing begins to dim. Conversations with my own papa, a couple of years Sir Roger’s junior, are increasingly punctuated with barks of “What say?!” and, more enigmatically, “What did Horace say, Winnie?” (the latter a catchphrase from some ancient comedian of his early youth).', 'But the blizzard of complaints about the BBC’s egregiously muffled dramatisation of Daphne du Maurier’s Jamaica Inn suggests that problems of audibility are not just in the ear of the hearer. Sir Roger blames television for the rise of the “mumbling school” of acting, but my experience of reviewing theatre for The Daily Telegraph makes me wonder if it is more complicated than that.', 'null', '0', '0', '1', '0', '1'),
(61, 'Benedict Cumberbatch told ''not to go into acting'' by leading Harrow drama teacher', 'Benedict Cumberbatch was encouraged not to enter the ‘tough business’ of acting by his drama teacher Martin Tyrrell, according to fellow schoolboy thespian.', 'TELEGRPAH.CO.UK', '2015-09-16 15:00:00', 4, 14, 0, 'benedict_small.jpg', 'benedict.jpg', '', '', 'The Oscar-nominated actor, pictured in The Sunday Times today playing Petruchio in a school production of Shakespeare''s The Taming of the Shrew at the Globe Theatre, greatly impressed in the performance.', 'The Oscar-nominated actor, pictured in The Sunday Times today playing Petruchio in a school production of Shakespeare''s The Taming of the Shrew at the Globe Theatre, greatly impressed in the performance.\r\nHowever he was advised not to pursue a career with his “dazzling” talent, according to Alexander Gifford, who performed alongside the young Cumberbatch in the play.\r\nMr Gifford, now a theatre director and playwright, told The Sunday Times: “Benedict was the complete star of the acting scene at Harrow and funnily enough I remember in that show...it was like he had gone to a whole new level and had a vitality on stage and an uninhibited freedom that was dazzling.\r\n"I do remember our drama teacher, Martin Tyrrell, advising him not to go into acting because it was such a tough business.\r\n“We were a really rich crop of young actors. We had Laurence Fox and Patrick Kennedy, and that was down to Mr Tyrrell. Benedict stood out as being preternaturally gifted."', 'null', '0', '0', '1', '0', '1'),
(62, 'Suffragette: Why are female film-makers rare?', 'Suffragette is a new British film written, directed and produced by women. Why is this still an oddity in the film industry? Rebecca Laurence reports for Talking Movies.', 'BBC', '2015-09-16 17:00:00', 4, 15, 0, 'female_film_small.jpg', 'female_film.jpg', '', '', 'It’s a defining part of modern British history, but the story of the Suffragettes – the women who campaigned for women’s voting rights – has not been shown on film before.', 'It’s a defining part of modern British history, but the story of the Suffragettes – the women who campaigned for women’s voting rights – has not been shown on film before.\r\nNow Suffragette, which stars Carey Mulligan, Helena Bonham-Carter and Meryl Streep, is set to address a piece of cinema’s missing history.\r\nBut by featuring women both in front of and behind the camera, the film highlights a gap in the industry. Why are there not more women making films and telling women’s stories?', 'null', '0', '0', '1', '0', '1'),
(63, 'Where Star Wars found new talent', 'Several of the young actors in The Force Awakens have something in common – they hail from Britain. Why are UK stars perfect for that galaxy far, far away?', 'BBC', '2015-09-16 17:00:00', 4, 15, 0, 'star_small.jpg', 'star.jpg', '', '', 'The Star Wars films have long been populated by British actors – including Alec Guinness and Peter Cushing in the original trilogy, Ewan McGregor in the prequel trilogy, and Ian McDiarmid who spanned both trios of films as the evil Emperor Palpatine. The sequel trilogy, beginning with The Force Awakens, continues this tradition: stars John Boyega, Daisy Ridley and Gwendoline Christie all hail from the UK.', 'The Star Wars films have long been populated by British actors – including Alec Guinness and Peter Cushing in the original trilogy, Ewan McGregor in the prequel trilogy, and Ian McDiarmid who spanned both trios of films as the evil Emperor Palpatine. The sequel trilogy, beginning with The Force Awakens, continues this tradition: stars John Boyega, Daisy Ridley and Gwendoline Christie all hail from the UK.\r\nAnd Star Wars is just one global franchise looking to Britain for up-and-coming talent. Marvel Studios cast 19-year-old Londoner Tom Holland in the role of Spider-Man.\r\nBut being a Briton in Hollywood can come with challenges – and none more imperative than learning to master an American accent. In fact, some British actors have become so associated with the American characters they play that audiences in the US don’t even know they’re British.\r\nFor Talking Movies, Al Moloney investigates the ongoing British Invasion of Hollywood.\r\nIf you would like to comment on this story or anything else you have seen on BBC Culture, head over to our Facebook page or message us on Twitter.', 'null', '0', '0', '0', '1', '1'),
(64, 'Marlon Brando: Rarely heard tapes', 'A new documentary pulls together previously unreleased recordings made by the elusive Hollywood star, offering an intimate portrait of an icon. Tom Brook talks to its director.', 'BBC', '2015-09-16 18:00:00', 4, 15, 0, 'marlon_small.jpg', 'marlon.jpg', '', '', 'Listen to me Marlon offers a portrait of Marlon Brando so intimate that Variety declared “it almost feels as if he assembled the film himself from beyond the grave”. The Hollywood star’s estate asked British film-maker Stevan Riley to make the documentary, drawing from hours of previously unreleased audio tapes.', 'Listen to me Marlon offers a portrait of Marlon Brando so intimate that Variety declared “it almost feels as if he assembled the film himself from beyond the grave”. The Hollywood star’s estate asked British film-maker Stevan Riley to make the documentary, drawing from hours of previously unreleased audio tapes.\r\n“There was a very ordinary and personable character behind all of that, who never wanted fame, who genuinely was a victim of his own success,” Riley tells Tom Brook. “I hope the film does a lot to bring him down to Earth, which is where he wanted to be.”\r\nExcerpts from the tapes are mixed with TV footage and home movies as well as clips from films including On the Waterfront and The Godfather. It’s a rare chance to see the human side of an icon. As Brando’s daughter Rebecca tells Brook, he was a man “filled with insecurities and self-doubt… always wanting to be approved and accepted, and validated.”\r\nIf you would like to comment on this story or anything else you have seen on BBC Culture, head over to our Facebook page or message us on Twitter.', 'null', '0', '0', '1', '0', '1'),
(65, 'Fantastic Four: The superhero on stilts', 'Jamie Bell (Billy Elliot) transforms into The Thing for Marvel’s latest reboot – and it made for interesting moments on set. While shooting Fantastic Four, the British actor had to wear a special motion capture suit and stand on stilts to give him hei', 'BBC', '2015-09-16 18:00:00', 4, 15, 0, 'fantastic_four_small.jpg', 'fantastic_four.jpg', '', '', 'Jamie Bell (Billy Elliot) transforms into The Thing for Marvel’s latest reboot – and it made for interesting moments on set. While shooting Fantastic Four, the British actor had to wear a special motion capture suit and stand on stilts to give him height.', 'Jamie Bell (Billy Elliot) transforms into The Thing for Marvel’s latest reboot – and it made for interesting moments on set. While shooting Fantastic Four, the British actor had to wear a special motion capture suit and stand on stilts to give him height.\r\n“It’s a little uncomfortable – because you can’t move the way you really want to move,” he tells Tom Brook. “It looks absurd, I’m basically wearing luminous green pyjamas with a little cap, on stilts. I’m surprised they could actually take me seriously at all in fairness, because it’s a pretty bad look.”\r\nBell and his co-stars Miles Teller (Whiplash), Kate Mara (House of Cards) and Michael B Jordan (The Wire) talk to Brook about what drew them to the story. “There’s a real co-dependency that has to happen here because our powers are so limited. It makes us rely on one another,” says Teller.\r\nIf you would like to comment on this story or anything else you have seen on BBC Culture, head over to our Facebook page or message us on Twitter.', 'null', '0', '0', '1', '0', '1'),
(66, 'Paris expo resurrects ancient Egypt’s lost city of Heracleion', 'After close to two millennia under water, the remains of the ancient Egyptian city of Heracleion have found a temporary home at the Arab World Institute in Paris.', 'FRANCE 24', '2015-09-16 16:00:00', 4, 16, 0, 'oziris_small.jpg', 'oziris.jpg', '', '', 'The exhibition “Osiris, Sunken Mysteries of Egypt” brings together some 2,500 artifacts from the legendary Nile Delta city, also known as Thonis, which is believed to have sunk at some point in the 2nd century AD and was one of the great port cities of the world.', 'After close to two millennia under water, the remains of the ancient Egyptian city of Heracleion have found a temporary home at the Arab World Institute in Paris.\r\n\r\nThe exhibition “Osiris, Sunken Mysteries of Egypt” brings together some 2,500 artifacts from the legendary Nile Delta city, also known as Thonis, which is believed to have sunk at some point in the 2nd century AD and was one of the great port cities of the world.\r\n\r\nThe precious objects, which have never before been exhibited in public, were recovered off the Egyptian coast by a French underwater archaeology team.\r\n\r\nFrench archaeologist Franck Goddio was looking for 18th-century French warships when he stumbled upon the completely submerged Heracleion.\r\n\r\nThe find sheds new light on the cult of Osiris, Ancient Egypt’s god of the afterlife and resurrection.\r\n\r\n“Osiris, Sunken Mysteries of Egypt” runs through January 31, 2016.\r\n\r\nClick on the player above to watch FRANCE 24''s report.', 'null', '0', '0', '1', '0', '1'),
(67, 'Stolen ''La Coiffeuse'' Picasso to be returned to France', '"La Coiffeuse", a cubist work by Pablo Picasso worth about $15 million, will be returned to France via the French embassy, ', 'FRANCE 24', '2015-09-16 16:00:00', 4, 16, 0, 'coiffeuse_small.jpg', 'coiffeuse.jpg', '', '', '"La Coiffeuse", a cubist work by Pablo Picasso worth about $15 million, will be returned to France via the French embassy, US officials said on Wednesday. The painting, whose name means "The Hairdresser", was stolen 14 years ago in Paris.', 'The 1911 cubist oil painting was smuggled out of a storeroom of the Georges Pompidou centre in 2001, The New York Times reported.\r\n\r\nThe painting, which had been bequeathed to the French government, was last exhibited in Munich in 1998 before being returned to Paris and stored at the Centre Pompidou, the paper said.\r\n\r\nOfficials at a shipping facility discovered the 33x46 centimetre (13x18 inch) painting wrapped in parcel paper when the package was inspected upon its arrival in Newark, New Jersey, in the weeks before Christmas last year. It had been sent from Belgium via the FedEx shipping company by someone who declared that the package contained an “art craft/toy” valued at €30 ($37) and with shipping documents reading "Joyeux Noël" (Merry Christmas).\r\n\r\nUS security authorities later transferred the painting to New York pending an investigation.\r\n\r\nFrench art experts travelled to New York in January to verify the authenticity of the work using photographs and historical records, eventually concluding that it was Picasso''s “La Coiffeuse”.\r\n\r\nUS Immigration and Customs Enforcement officials said the painting would be returned via the French embassy in Washington, DC.\r\n\r\nAnother Picasso worth more than €25 million that was seized from a yacht off the French island of Corsica earlier this month was transferred to a Madrid museum on Tuesday.\r\n\r\nThat painting, which was considered a national treasure by Spanish authorities who had banned it from being exported, was seized by French customs at the end of July.', 'null', '0', '0', '1', '0', '1'),
(68, 'Another Benefit of Fish Oil: It May Reduce Weight Gain From Fatty Foods', 'Ordering the “catch of the day” may help keep your waistline from expanding every time you eat a french fry.', 'BBC', '2015-09-16 19:00:00', 7, 25, 0, 'fish_oli_small.jpg', 'fish_oli.jpg', '', '', 'According to a new study, adding more fish to your diet or taking fish oil supplements could counteract the effects of a greasy diet and help you shed some weight.', 'According to a new study, adding more fish to your diet or taking fish oil supplements could counteract the effects of a greasy diet and help you shed some weight.\r\n\r\nSwedish researchers at Sahlgrenska Academy in Gothenburg arrived at this conclusion after cooking up two different menus for mice in their labs.big breakfast CC Rene Schwietzke\r\n\r\nThe Perfect Healthy Breakfasts When You’re in a Hurry (It’s not the one you see here!)\r\n\r\nSome of them ate lard-based meals, while the others dined on meals rich in fish oil. The two different diets allowed for different kinds of microbes to flourish inside each respective group of mice.\r\n\r\nThe lard-based diet promoted growth of a bacteria called Bilophila, which has been linked to inflammation. Mice eating the fish oil diet saw higher levels of a different bacteria called Akkermansia muciniphila, which has been linked to improved metabolism and slowing weight gain.\r\n', 'null', '0', '0', '1', '0', '1'),
(69, '“Man Therapy” Uses Humor To Target Serious Mental Health Issues For Bros', 'Dr. Rich Mahogany, a fictional therapist with a mental health message for men only, uses ‘bro’.', 'BBC', '2015-09-16 15:00:00', 7, 25, 0, 'therapy_small.jpg', 'therapy.jpg', '', '', 'The sometimes crude humor cuts through the stigma of mental illness to address the pressures of masculinity. Being the strong, silent type—never sharing emotions until they’ve reached a boiling point–can take a dangerous toll on mental health. ‘Dr. Mahogany’ prods men to “get off their keisters” and try exercises and tips to help improve their well-being.', 'The sometimes crude humor cuts through the stigma of mental illness to address the pressures of masculinity. Being the strong, silent type—never sharing emotions until they’ve reached a boiling point–can take a dangerous toll on mental health. ‘Dr. Mahogany’ prods men to “get off their keisters” and try exercises and tips to help improve their well-being.\r\n\r\nThe site was developed in 2012, originally designed to reach men in Colorado, a state with one of the highest suicide rates in the country. Its appeal has since stretched far beyond Colorado; in the past three years, Man Therapy has attracted three quarters of a million views.1967-Lamborghini-2-cc-Rex-Gray\r\n\r\nShe Sold Late Husband’s Lamborghini, Raised $500K for Suicide Prevention\r\n\r\nSuicide is the tenth leading cause of death for adults in the U.S. and men are most at risk–accounting for 78% of fatalities in 2013, according to the American Foundation for Suicide Prevention.\r\n\r\nThe Man Therapy team of mental health experts is especially focused on reaching a specific group, what they call “double-jeopardy men,” working guys with the most risk factors who are the least likely to seek help. They use language that can resonate with these men who might otherwise not want to think about their mental wellbeing.\r\nManTherapy.org is a nonprofit collaboration between the Colorado Office of Suicide Prevention, The Carson J. Spencer Foundation and the advertising agency, Cactus.\r\n\r\nThe website will soon come out with a new version that can be customized, allowing users to match resources with individual needs.\r\n\r\nOffering, as Dr. Rich Mahogany would say, “Therapy the way a man would do it.”', 'null', '0', '0', '1', '0', '1'),
(70, 'Tough Going for Health Co-ops', 'Late last month, the Nevada Health Co-op became the third casualty ', 'BBC', '2015-09-16 16:00:00', 7, 26, 0, 'patient_room_small.jpg', 'patient_room.jpg', '', '', 'Set up as nonprofits with consumer-led boards, the co-ops were designed to provide affordable insurance coverage to individuals and small businesses. They were intended under the law to offer alternatives — and hopefully cheaper prices — to the plans sold by large established insurance companies in some regions.', 'Set up as nonprofits with consumer-led boards, the co-ops were designed to provide affordable insurance coverage to individuals and small businesses. They were intended under the law to offer alternatives — and hopefully cheaper prices — to the plans sold by large established insurance companies in some regions.\r\n\r\nBut as the new co-ops begin failing just a year into the effort to remake the health care industry with more competition and lower costs, the marketplace is proving hostile to newcomers trying to break into an industry dominated by powerfully entrenched businesses.', 'null', '0', '0', '1', '0', '1'),
(71, 'Obama Looks to Take Budget Fight to G.O.P.', 'WASHINGTON — Congress hurtled toward a government shutdown on Tuesday', 'BBC', '2015-09-16 17:00:00', 7, 26, 0, 'gop_small.jpg', 'gop.jpg', '', '', 'WASHINGTON — Congress hurtled toward a government shutdown on Tuesday, with Republicans threatening to block a budget deal if it includes financing for Planned Parenthood, as President Obama prepared to join the fight by pushing Republicans to scrap a multibillion-dollar tax advantage for private equity managers.', 'WASHINGTON — Congress hurtled toward a government shutdown on Tuesday, with Republicans threatening to block a budget deal if it includes financing for Planned Parenthood, as President Obama prepared to join the fight by pushing Republicans to scrap a multibillion-dollar tax advantage for private equity managers.\r\n\r\nIn a speech on Wednesday, Mr. Obama is expected to call on Republicans to end the tax break and use the funds to pay for spending increases on domestic and national security programs, and he will enlist business leaders to help him make his case.\r\n\r\nIn a session at the Business Roundtable in Washington, Mr. Obama will seek to shame Republicans who control Congress for failing to strike a deal with Democrats to fund the government’s operations, using the so-called carried-interest provision as an example of what he argues are misplaced priorities, according to White House officials.', 'null', '0', '0', '1', '0', '1'),
(72, 'The amazing health benefits of honey', 'Honey has some fantastic natural health benefits and can been used to treat a variety of conditions – boosting the immune system, improving digestion, healing wounds', 'BBC', '2015-09-16 18:00:00', 7, 27, 0, 'honey_small.jpg', 'honey.jpg', '', '', 'This is the first article in a 3 part series. Today we will learn all about honey, it’s great health benefits and what is so special about manuka honey. Stay tuned – later we will look at how you can use honey at home with some fabulous DIY beauty tips (like the honey turmeric mask) and home remedies as well as some delicious healthy recipes.', 'What is honey?\r\nA quick refresher… Honey is a sweet food that bees make using sugary nectar collected from flowers. They transform this nectar into honey through a regurgitation process (sounds a bit gross I know – basically they process it until it reaches a desired quality), and this is stored in wax honeycombs inside a beehive. The bees then fan the honeycomb to encourage evaporation of water – this prevents fermentation. Pretty clever, huh? The raw honey that beekeepers collect from the hive has a long shelf life and won’t ferment if it is sealed well.\r\n \r\nDid you know that honey won’t freeze solid? It just becomes really thick and sluggish at low temperatures. Don’t we all!?\r\n \r\nThere are many different types of honey – each with a unique flavour, appearance and quality – this is determined by what flowers the bees have been visiting. You can buy either a pure floral honey or a commercial blend (different types mixed together). Honey is processed in many ways – so you can end up with a lot of different forms of honey including crystallized honey, pasteurized honey, raw honey, strained honey, filtered honey, ultrasonicated honey, whipped honey, dried honey, comb honey and chunk honey. Phew!\r\n \r\nHoney nutrition\r\nHoney maintains most of it’s vitamins and minerals if kept raw and unheated . As there are so many different types of honey, the nutritional composition and quality varies. Honey can contain calcium, zinc, iron, Vitamin C, magnesium, potassium and B vitamins (B1, B2, B3, B5 & B6). It is a natural energy booster, since it is mostly (around 84%) made up of sugars – glucose and fructose, which leads us to our next question…\r\n \r\nHoney vs sugar – which is healthier?\r\nWhile honey contains the same basic sugar units as table sugar, it is chemically different – in table sugar the glucose and fructose are linked together, while in honey they remain separate. A lot of processed food tends to contain granulated sugar with high levels of fructose which converts to fat more easily than honey. No thanks! Honey takes longer to digest than sugar and offers more sustained energy – it has a low to medium GI (pure honey has a lower GI than blended honey) and some athletes even use honey to help performance endurance and ease muscle fatigue. Research has shown that honey keeps blood sugar levels more constant than other types of sugar. In addition, honey is less processed than sugar and contains more minerals and vitamins. Even though honey is generally considered more healthy than sugar, it’s not a free ticket to have as much as you want! We should consume all sugars in moderation – including honey. Honey actually has more calories than table sugar but we tend to use it less because it tastes sweeter.\r\n \r\nHoney has antioxidant properties (it can remove free radicals from the body) and can improve the digestive system. It is considered by many as an all-round health and immune system booster. There are some claims that honey may have anti-tumour properties and may prevent carcinogens, but this is not scientifically proven.\r\n \r\nWhen you are shopping for honey to eat, check the labels for raw (minimally processed and not heated, so it retains vitamins and minerals) and pure (lower GI than blended honey). Raw honey is so good for you that many people call it a superfood!\r\n \r\nMedicinal benefits of honey\r\nHoney has traditionally been used to treat a variety of ailments and is found in many natural home remedies. Recent scientific research (like the work done by the Waikato Honey Research Unit) is confirming the nutritional and medicinal properties of natural honey and how it can be used in modern medicine.', 'null', '0', '0', '1', '0', '1'),
(73, 'Barefoot running (with shoes on)', 'This week I got my first pair of “barefoot” running shoes. I know, it sounds like a contradiction but stick with me here…', 'BBC', '2015-09-16 15:00:00', 7, 27, 0, 'barefoot_running_small.jpg', 'barefoot_running.jpg', '', '', 'I have always loved running on the beach, but thought that it was more about the feeling of running on soft sand than being barefoot. But thinking about it now, the barefoot aspect is a big part of why I like it – it’s the feeling of freedom, simplicity and connecting with nature. I love all kinds of beach sports and inherently barefoot exercise like yoga, pilates and swimming,', 'I have always loved running on the beach, but thought that it was more about the feeling of running on soft sand than being barefoot. But thinking about it now, the barefoot aspect is a big part of why I like it – it’s the feeling of freedom, simplicity and connecting with nature. I love all kinds of beach sports and inherently barefoot exercise like yoga, pilates and swimming, and I can’t wait to try stand up paddle boarding (hope to do this very soon). At home and in the garden, I’m pretty much always barefoot, except for Wintery nights when I keep my feet warm with some nice thick wool socks. I don’t really do high heels. So now that I think about it, I’m pretty keen on the whole barefoot thing already. At a school camp to Fraser Island (which is stunning), I was fascinated by our guide who told us he had been barefoot for many years, except for formal occasions. I think I even took a photo of his feet (when he wasn’t looking)! And having grown up in South Africa in the 80′s, I saw Zola Budd – a South African runner who famously raced barefoot.\r\n\r\nBut I’ve never really considered running around the streets barefoot. It doesn’t seem practical, I think I’d be too worried about watching the path for rocks, glass and the like to enjoy the run. So when I heard about “barefoot” running shoes, or minimalist running shoes – that sparked my interest.\r\n \r\nWhy all the fuss over barefoot running?\r\nBarefoot running, also called natural running uses a different running form to the one we usually adopt when running with cushioned running shoes. When running barefoot, you land on the middle or ball of your foot, with a bent knee – as opposed to “normal” running, where you typically land with a longer stride, on your heel with your leg straight out in front of you. Barefoot advocates argue that the biomechanics of barefoot running result in less impact to your joints and body, and may help runners avoid chronic injuries caused by the impact of heel striking. They also claim that regularly running barefoot strengthens the arch of your food, which can naturally help dampen the impact of running. By adopting a good barefoot running technique, you can expect better balance, stability, lighter impact and increased propulsion. Many barefoot runners are inspired by the book Born to Run by Christopher McDougall, which follows a tribe of barefoot distance runners in Mexico.', 'null', '0', '0', '1', '1', '1'),
(74, 'Healthy vietnamese food with Luke Nguyen', ' I went to an amazing cooking demonstration by Luke Nguyen – at Delectable, a food festival in Brisbane. ', 'BBC', '2015-09-16 20:00:00', 7, 27, 0, 'luke_small.jpg', 'luke.jpg', '', '', 'On Saturday I went to an amazing cooking demonstration by Luke Nguyen – at Delectable, a food festival in Brisbane. Luke is an awesome chef and I love watching Luke Nguyen’s Vietnam, where he travels through Vietnam cooking street food. He also hosts food tours through Vietnam, which would be a sensational experience (maybe one day!). Apparently the ladies who cook street food in Vietnam often specialise in just one dish, cooking that same dish for 30 to 40 years, so you know it’s going to be good!', 'Luke told us how Vietnamese food is all about texture, freshness and healthiness. It’s often packed with loads of fresh herbs and spices, which not only add brilliant flavour, but also have medicinal value. Luke explained how his family taught him about the healing power of these herbs and spices as he was growing up. The class was great, full of personal stories and anecdotes, as well as some amazing food! Nothing too fancy-pants – just simple, authentic flavours. We are so lucky in Queensland to have fantastic produce all year around, so we can always cook beautiful healthy food using fresh, local and sustainable organic produce.\r\n \r\n \r\nThe dishes Luke showed us were:\r\nTurmeric & lemongrass coral trout, steamed in banana leafTurmeric & lemongrass coral trout, steamed in banana leaf\r\nThis is really healthy, smelt divine and looked amazing. I can’t wait to try it at home! You can view a very similar recipe here. The salad you see on top is made of green papaya, perilla leaves, vietnamese mint leaves and goji berries – yum!\r\nTip: banana leaf not only seals and protects the fish in the steamer (and looks pretty cool), it also adds flavour.', 'null', '0', '0', '1', '0', '1'),
(75, 'Savour your food, it’s good for you!', 'Most of us are guilty of rushing through our meals at times. Whether it’s stress, hunger, a sheer lack of time or something else – there are many excuses for inhaling food. In fact,', 'BBC', '2015-09-16 19:00:00', 7, 27, 0, 'benefits_small.jpg', 'benefits.jpg', '', '', 'When was the last time you took the time to truly savour a meal? By this I mean eating slowly and thoughtfully – appreciating the smell, flavour, texture of each bite. And more than that… Also pausing to think about the food – where it came from, how it was grown, who prepared it and how it was made. When you think about it, a lot of people probably put in a lot of effort to grow the food and get it from the farm to your plate. Don’t we owe them the respect of truly appreciating each mouthful instead of mindlessly wolfing it down?', 'Why is chewing so important?\r\nChewing is the first step of digestion. If food is not chewed well, the rest of the digestion process can suffer. There are two main reasons for this. First of all, chewing increases the surface area of the food. Secondly, saliva helps start digesting food – it contains enzymes that start breaking down carbohydrates and fats. It also helps move the food through your gut. The more you chew, the easier it will be to digest later on. On top of that, it is thought that the longer you savour your food through seeing, smelling and tasting – the more your body will be prepared to fully digest it. Complete digestion means that you’ll be reaping the benefits of absorbing all the nutrients out of the food, rather than them going to waste. There’s not much point in eating super healthy food if your body isn’t going to be able to make the most out of all those nutrients!\r\nWhy eating too fast can be bad for your health\r\nWhen you eat too fast, your body may not be able to fully digest the food. Incomplete digestion is not easy on the stomach and can cause a few problems, including heartburn, stomach pain, bloating, gas, wind and other indigestion discomfort. The long term effects of poor digestion can lead to health problems including nutrient deficiencies and food sensitivities. If food isn’t digested properly, it can lead to bacterial overgrowth in your gut which can cause wind. This is especially important for people who eat a lot of red meat, as it is quite dense and difficult to break down. Throwing down a meal in seconds can also increase the risk of choking, as large pieces of food can get lodged in the windpipe. And finally… Fast eating also means that you are probably swallowing a bit of air with your food, which can make you gassy and bloated. Same goes with fast drinking!', 'null', '0', '0', '1', '0', '1'),
(76, 'Samsung''s First Foldable Smartphone Due in January: Report', 'We have been hearing rumours about a Samsung foldable phone in the works for more than two years now, with the company showing off several prototypes of folding displays as well.', 'NEW YORK TIMES', '2015-09-16 17:00:00', 5, 17, 0, 'samsung_small.jpg', 'samsung.jpg', '', '', 'The South Korean company in the meantime has launched Galaxy smartphones with curved edge displays. If a new leak is to be believed, we might finally see a foldable Samsung smartphone in January - with the company reportedly already testing the smartphone. Additionally, Samsung''s mysterious Galaxy View device has been certified by the Bluetooth SIG claiming it''s a tablet.', 'The South Korean company in the meantime has launched Galaxy smartphones with curved edge displays. If a new leak is to be believed, we might finally see a foldable Samsung smartphone in January - with the company reportedly already testing the smartphone. Additionally, Samsung''s mysterious Galaxy View device has been certified by the Bluetooth SIG claiming it''s a tablet.\r\n\r\nAccording to a tipster from China (via GforGames), Samsung''s foldable smartphone has been codenamed Project Valley and is being tested with two different chipsets - Qualcomm Snapdragon 620 and Snapdragon 820. Other details tipped by the tipster claim that the handset will feature 3GB of RAM; come with expandable storage, and will come with an embedded battery.\r\n\r\nIt''s worth noting that a previous report had claimed that Samsung was testing the unannounced Qualcomm Snapdragon 820 chipset ''aggressively''. The test results were said to determine if the chipset would be featured in next year''s flagship models or not.\r\n\r\nIn other news, Samsung''s mysterious Galaxy View device which was teased during its IFA event and expected to the oft-leaked 18.4-inch tablet from the company has purportedly been certified by Bluetooth SIG with model name SM-T670. The Bluetooth SIG listing of the tablet doesn''t reveal many details; except that the Bluetooth version will be 4.1.\r\n\r\nTo recall, Samsung just as it did at the Galaxy Unpacked event last month, teased a new upcoming product at the end of the IFA show - what appeared to be a large tablet. Dubbed Galaxy View, the teaser was mysterious enough to hide most details but a kick stand was visible on the back panel. We will have to wait for Samsung to make the announcement.', 'null', '0', '0', '0', '1', '1'),
(77, 'Sony Xperia Z5 Premium Only Renders Video and Image Content in 4K', 'Sony''s Xperia Z5 Premium is no doubt the world''s first smartphone featuring a 4K display ', 'NEW YORK TIMES', '2015-09-16 14:00:00', 5, 17, 0, 'z5_small.jpg', 'z5.jpg', '', '', 'Sony''s Xperia Z5 Premium is no doubt the world''s first smartphone featuring a 4K display with a resolution of 2160x3840 pixels and an impressive pixel density of 806ppi. The new Sony phone however, even before going up for sale, is under scrutiny for not displaying a 4K resolution all across the UI.', 'Sony''s Xperia Z5 Premium is no doubt the world''s first smartphone featuring a 4K display with a resolution of 2160x3840 pixels and an impressive pixel density of 806ppi. The new Sony phone however, even before going up for sale, is under scrutiny for not displaying a 4K resolution all across the UI.\r\n\r\nDuring the time we spent with Xperia Z5 Premium at IFA we noted that screenshots captured from the Z5 Premium were actually of 1080p resolution. We checked with Sony executives present at the launch event about the same but did not receive any kind of explanation. Now, Sony has provided an official answer.\r\n\r\n"Xperia Z5 Premium features a 4K display with a resolution of 3840x2160 pixels based on SID Standard and enables all video and image content to be enjoyed in 4K resolution. All other content is displayed at 1080P or lower resolution in order to optimise the performance and battery stamina for this device, ensuring you can enjoy the 4K resolution when you need it most," Sony said in a statement to Phonearena.\r\n\r\nTo recall, Sony at the IFA launch had claimed that its new Sony Xperia Z5, Xperia Z5 Compact, and Xperia Z5 Premium can offer up to 2 days of battery life. Sony''s optimisation technology for content viewing on the handset now explains how the Xperia Z5 Premium even with a massive screen resolution is expected to deliver up to 2 days of battery life.\r\n\r\nThe Japanese company has been lately been part of a controversy that questioned the waterproof capabilities of its devices. Sony started warning its users that they shouldn''t use their Xperia devices (whether smartphone or tablet) underwater. To do so, will void the device''s warranty, the company added.\r\n\r\nTo note, most companies shipping smartphones with QHD (2K) displays, including Sony with the Xperia Z4v, natively show all content in QHD resolution, taxing the batteries and processors on the phone. Also notable, is that for regular UI and browsing, the Xperia Z5 Premium with its 4K display would look less sharp than most 2K QHD smartphones.', 'null', '0', '0', '1', '0', '1'),
(78, 'LG Teases Smartphone Launch on Monday, ''Class'' Mid-Range Phablet Tipped', 'LG Electronics has teased an upcoming smartphone to arrive on Monday via social channels. Additionally', 'BBC', '2015-09-16 19:00:00', 5, 17, 0, 'lg_small.jpg', 'lg.jpg', '', '', 'LG Electronics has teased an upcoming smartphone to arrive on Monday via social channels. Additionally, an LG device codenamed H740, believed to be the same device launching on Monday, has been spotted in a benchmark listing.', 'LG Electronics has teased an upcoming smartphone to arrive on Monday via social channels. Additionally, an LG device codenamed H740, believed to be the same device launching on Monday, has been spotted in a benchmark listing.\r\n\r\nSharing the teaser image on Facebook, an LG device with rear power and volume rocker buttons was seen, sporting a metallic body and a straight-edged look. The tagline in the image said, "Something New." By looking at the image, the new LG device seems to be a mid-range handset featuring a different design compared to the flagships LG G3 or even LG G4.\r\n\r\nSteve Hemmerstoffer of Nowhereelse.fr claims that the upcoming ''Something New'' devices is a mid-range phablet called the LG Class.', 'null', '0', '0', '1', '0', '1');
